      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07561'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_334' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Page 78, line 50, leave out ("subsection (3)(a)") and insert ("subsection (3)&#x2014;
        <q>(i) in paragraph (a),").</q>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07562'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_335' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Earl said: These are detailed but, I suggest, useful amendments to Sections 12 and 18 of the <a href="/acts/adoption-scotland-act-1978">Adoption (Scotland) Act 1978</a>. Amendments Nos. 206C, 206K, 206L, 206M and 206P are minor consequential amendments.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07563'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_336' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Under existing legislation, if a child who is under a supervision requirement is placed for adoption or a court decides that he should be freed for adoption, it is necessary for the children's hearing to review the case before the supervision can be terminated.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07564'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_337' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Where the supervision requirement arose from a need to protect the child and not because of difficulties with his own behaviour, there would almost certainly be no need for it to continue, given the arrangements being made for the child's adoption. The review hearing in those particular circumstances is an unnecessary bureaucratic step which could be hurtful to the new parents. A similar situation arises in relation to freeing orders.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07565'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_338' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The amendments ensure that where a court is making an adoption or freeing order and it is clear that there is no continuing need for a supervision requirement, the court has the power to terminate that requirement.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07566'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_339' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        As I said, the other amendments are consequential on this main provision. I beg to move.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07567'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_340' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        On Question, amendments agreed to.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07568'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_341' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <span class="member">The Earl of Lindsay</span> moved Amendment No. 206E:
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-07569'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950613_GCR_342' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Page 78, line 51, at end insert ("; and
